====So, what //is// abjection?==== 
====Each individual will face events in their life that threaten their identity or subjecthood. At these times when something disturbs his or her identity a person feels as though the threatening //__thing__// contaminates him or her//.// The Subject therefore attempts to create a border that keeps this disturbing //__thing__//away. The //__thing__//is thus cast away and expelled. This is abjection.==== 
<span style="font-size: 13pt;">Sjoholm 5</span>(Cecilia, Senior Lecturer at the University of Sotodern in Comparative Literature, __Kristeva and the Political,__ 2005)

__As Kristeva herself ...__<span style="font-size: 8pt;"> keep them apart</span>

====Abjection is the expulsion of this previously mentioned //__thing__//signified by the abject. The abject is that creepy phenomenon we separate from ourselves. This inner experience is an inherently indeterminable process, since it focuses on the liminal – or utterly ambiguous – phenomenon that produces affective connections to the subject. The occurrence that disturbs a subject’s identity provokes the experience of abjection.==== 
<span style="font-size: 13pt;">Sjoholm 5</span>(Cecilia, Senior Lecturer at the University of Sotodern in Comparative Literature, __Kristeva and the Political__, 2005)

__One of the__ __...__<span style="font-size: 8pt;"> this very rejection. </span>

====Corpses and blood represent abjects. Society determines that they must be cast away because they are tenebrous and therefore understood as gross. Each superego is relegated an abject because the superego chooses to abhor and reject a given object.==== 
<span style="font-size: 13pt;">Sjoholm 5</span>(Cecilia, Senior Lecturer at the University of Sotodern in Comparative Literature, __Kristeva and the Political,__ 2005)

__Abjection is ...__<span style="font-size: 8pt;"> contour through disgust. </span>

====Abjection is a repressive process in which the self is forced to repress phenomena because they are quote-on-quote “dangerous”. This puts one into a constant state of defense. The world cannot just be. But, rather, must be cleansed of all abjects. Therefore, we engage in a constant attempt to actualize a fantasy in which there are no abjects. But abjects are inevitable. Attempting to escape this both creates violent lash outs against any perceived abject, and destroys any hope of worthwhile existence for the abjecting individual creating a constant feeling of dejection.==== 

<span style="font-size: 13pt;">Sjoholm 5</span>(Cecilia, Senior Lecturer at the University of Sotodern in Comparative Literature, __Kristeva and the Political,__ 2005)

