====<span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 14pt;">This year we are posed the question whether United States Federal Government should invest in transportation infrastructure. Traditionally, an affirmative team will investigate a concrete policy to alter transportation infrastructure. However, we choose to confront the abjects inherent in the resolution. </span>==== 
====<span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 14pt;">This mode of interrogation makes it immediately clear that there is an integral connection between the resolution, individuation, and abjection. The resolution provides several liminal spaces that can disrupt an individual’s identity – these liminal spaces are abjected. That is, no one reads affirmatives surrounding the affective connections to identity that these forms of transportation infrastructure provide. </span>==== 
====<span style="font-family: 'Times New Roman',serif; font-size: 14pt;">So, we isolate three liminal spaces and choose to confront, and affirm, them. In so affirming, we are able to negate abjection in the context of the resolution, and the debate sphere. Thus, we encounter the pleasure of our organic mind, less the superego, through the ballot.</span>==== 

<span style="display: block; text-align: left;">Thus the liminal spaces:</span>
====First is the road. The road functions as an intermediary zone that bridges childhood and adulthood. While the street provides the chance for the child to feel free, to play football, or to run around; it also provides the adult the feeling of freedom because driving invokes an explicitly joyous reaction, since it is the act of enjoying on one’s own. Further, it provokes a malaise concerning the dangers of the road. The road is a sphere where the subject achieves a new form of agency that abandons the age-concerned superego, and rather creates an entropic identity. This conjures an experience that rejects the superego. Society therefore abjects it.==== 
<span style="font-size: 13pt;">Christensen and O’Brien 3</span>(Pia and Margaret, Senior Researcher at the National Institute of Public Health, Copenhagen, Denmark and professor of psychosocial studies at the University of East Anglia, __Children in the City: Home, Neighborhood, and Community__, 2003)

<span style="font-size: 8pt;">She describes how ...</span>__demolishing of structures.”__

====Second is the airport. The airport is another scape of abjection that subverts the repressive superego. It is a zone that exists between two places – the earth and the sky. For this reason, it is ambiguous. It is a place where the subject temporarily waits. However, it is a non-place in because it has no use other than to be a distracton. The airport borders both anxiety and pleasure and in this way is subjectively disturbing.==== 
<span style="font-size: 13pt;">Lloyd 3</span> (Justine, University of Technology, Sydney, “Airport Technology, Travel, and Consumption”, Sagepub, 2003)

<span style="font-size: 8pt;">This pleasurable postfunctionalism ...</span> __“increasing per-passenger dwelltime”__<span style="font-size: 8pt;"> (Chandler, 2002, p. 2).</span>

====Third is the urban, the suburban, and the journey between the two. The urban and suburban correspond to the masculine-feminine dichotomy, respectively, and in both locations these two phenomena externally impose an identity on the subject. The journey between the two is ambiguous in terms of identity because it is neither masculine nor feminine, but is affected by both. Not only is the subject’s identity externally imposed on them but it is an unknown external imposition and is therefore abjected because the superego fears subsumption.==== 
<span style="font-size: 13pt;">Brooks 98</span>(Brooks, Karen. "Shit Creek: Suburbia, Abjection And Subjectivity In Australian 'Grunge' Fiction." Australian Literary Studies 18.4 (1998): 87. Academic Search Complete.Web. 21 Dec. 2012.)

